		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> LOTR Q&A Rulings from 04/24/03<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.50)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617'>Enrique "Max of Tat" Huerta</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> June 5, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> NOT FOR REVIEW!!!<br />
=================<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Hello All!!<br />
<br />
   Sorry for the late update everybody. I&#39;m in Orlando for the weekend to help direct the Junior High National Chess Championships. (See I do run more than just LOTR tournaments!) (= And since I can&#39;t sleep and don&#39;t feel like paying $5 to listen to Maid in Manhattan, I think I&#39;ll update my article.<br />
<br />
   I ran a Standard tournament this past weekend, and I must say it was a refreshing change of pace. The top 5 decks were completely different on both the Fellowship and Shadow sides. Looks like the players will need a little bit of time to determine what works in the format, but until then I will enjoy seeing Sauron, Isengard Orcs and maybe even my beloved Dwarves in some winner&#39;s circles.<br />
<br />
   Looks like it was a light week for rules questions. No problem, just makes my job easier.<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
<br />
Return home soon, Carlos.<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about LOTR Rulings:</h3><br />
<br />
<b> What would this section be Without questions from me? Probably easier, but that&#39;s beside the point :) Anywho, this weeks questions regards exerting and healing. 1. Can I discard a copy of a companion to heal a companion who is not wounded? 2. Can I exert a frodo signet companion to &quot;heal&quot; Frodo, Son of Drogo, even if he doesn&#39;t have a wound? 3. Can I exert Galadriel, Lady of the Golden Wood, to play my next site, even if it isn&#39;t a forest (ie NOT play my next site), or if my next site is already out? My guess is NO, YES and NO, but just want clarification. Thanks again. [Nexus X]<br />
<br />
Oops antoehr question, this time on ents. Can I discard multiple times in the assignement phase, or exert an unbound hobbit and discard cards? thanks [Nexus X] </b><br />
<br />
1. No. The rule that allows you to dicard a copy of a unique companion or ally during Fellowship phase to heal that character also requires you to &quot;spot a wound&quot; on that character. If you can&#39;t spot the wound you can&#39;t meet the requirements to play the action.<br />
<br />
2. Yes. This is different than the above situation because there is not requirement for a wound to be on a character in order to attempt to heal the character. You would pay the costs of the action but the effects (healing Frodo) would be ignored.<br />
<br />
3. This is an interesting question. According to the rules you must play a card if the action that requires to play a card from your hand or discard pile. It make no mention of having to play the card if it&#39;s from your adventure deck. I would have to say that YES you can exert Galadriel, Lady of the Golden Wood, but you do not have to play your next site. This would be true whether or not it&#39;s a Forest or still in your Adventure Deck. (NOTE: You can still only play it if it&#39;s a Forest and in your adventure deck!) (= <br />
<br />
4. Yes. You can perform an action multiple times, as long as you&#39;re able to pay the costs, even if that action will have no effect.<br />
<br />
<b>I have three questions 1) Can you do more than one responce per action. Example: If the ring bearer puts on the Ring can you exert multiple uruk spies as responce actions? 2) For Eowyn, Daughter of Eomund can you play a weapon on her in the manuever phase if she has no wounds? 3)Can you discard a non-unique character to heal that character in play? [Edwin] </b><br />
	<br />
1. Yes. You can respond to the same action more than once. You can also uses the same Response special ability (bold &quot;Response:&quot;) more than once on the same card as long as you&#39;re able to pay the cost. If the Ring-bearer puts on the One Ring and you have multiple Uruk Spies out, you may use the Response action for each of them.<br />
<br />
2. Yes. As mentioned with Nexus X&#39;s second question you can initiate actions to heal a character even if the action will have no effect. The only exception if the Fellowship action of Spotting a wound and discarding a copy of a unique companion or ally.<br />
<br />
3. No. The rule is specific in that you can only use the Fellowship action for unique companions and allies.<br />
<br />
<b> Quick, probably easy question. In an Uruk Machine Deck if I have more than one siege engines out do i get to add a token for each siege engine in play or just one per Uruk. [Demetri] </b><br />
<br />
I assume you&#39;re talking about the Shadow action of playing an Uruk-hai to add an [Isengard] token to a machine. No, you do not get to add a token to a machine mulitple times if you play 1 Uruk-hai when you have multiple Siege Engines in play. The reason is that the gametext on Siege Engine is a phase actions and you can only play one phase action at a time. The cost of that phase action is to &quot;play an Uruk-hai&quot;. You can not use that cost to pay for multiple actions. For example you can not just add one twilight to the pool in order to play 2 hobbit swords, a elven bow, and a Dwarf Guard. Please note the difference between these cards and Goblin Armory. Goblin Armory isn&#39;t a phase action, but a response to playing a [Moria] weapon. You can response to the same action (or trigger) multiple times.<br />
<br />
<b> Can I exert common Saruman to make one of my Uurks fight an Ent? If that works, would he have to discard 2 cards to allow the skirmish, or could he choose not to discard 2 and not have him fight? [Bill] </b><br />
<br />
You may exert Saruman, Servant of the Eye however you may not make your minion skirmish an Unhasty Ent unless that Ent is an ally at it&#39;s Home Site. The reason is that an Unhasty character may only participate in skirmishes (i.e. be assigned to a skirmish) if that character is an ally at it&#39;s Home Site or it&#39;s a [Gandalf] card that is allowing it to do so. Saruman is not a [Gandalf] card, therefore it would only have an effect is it&#39;s used against an ally at it&#39;s Home Site. (Note: If another card has already allowed the Unhasty Ent to participate in skirmish, then YES you can use Saruman, Servant of the Eye to assign a minion to that Ent.)<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about LOTR Meta:</h3><br />
<br />
<b> Enrique, LotR CCG is a competitive game, but good sportsmanship is important also. Two issues concern me when playing at local shops. First, the lack of using a timer and allowing players a few moments to find their opponent, get seated, assure that decks have been adequately shuffled, and then starting the round time so that everyone is treated the same. One player was almost indignant that I required he shuffle his deck in front of me - claim he had &quot;shuffled it at home&quot;. Good grief - everyone knows that they need to randomly shuffled their deck in front of their opponent. My opponent took so long to do it that he dragged out the game at site 8 simply because he only had Frodo left, but had no burdens and time was called before he decided whether or not to move onto the next site or reconcile his hand. This kind of behavior ruins the fun part of the game. Also the shop is not making a timer/clock available for all to use. Maybe I&#39;ll bring a chess clock to know how the time is transpiring. And two, when the shop keeper plays since he decides when time is up his games always go until site 9 is reached unless it is prudent that it be over because he is ahead, but realizes he can&#39;t stop his opponent&#39;s next two moves to site 9 and victory. I would like to see Decipher be firmer about assuring that one all players have ten minutes after pairings are announced to find their seat, get tokens out, starting fellowships, and initial shuffel before actual game time is used, i.e. bidding , re-shuffling if necessary (starting fellowship changed)etc. should be during game time. And a visible clock available to all players be used to assure time is not called arbitrarily or extended at someone&#39;s whim. Finally, to assure stalling near the end of time is not unfair, I believe that once time is called the active, fellowship player should finish their turn and the other player finish one full turn. Another option is that the second player, player who moved second at the start of the game has the last turn - if time is called on their turn then they complete it and that ends the game, or if time is called on the first player&#39;s to moves turn the he or she finishes her turn and the second player gets one last turn. The second player should always end the game to assure that both players had an equal number of turns witht the fellowship. This must be addressed by Decipher, because decks such as Moria based decks need an opportunity at site 9 because their deck is designed to swarm at site nine and opponents can stall by making assignments slowly, etc. at earlier sites to have the game end before their fellowship has to march to site 9 and survive the Moria Swarm in order to win. I would like to see the rules adjusted to assure good sportsmanship and assure that all deck types have a chance to succeed. Some decks take longer to cycle through cards like Moria and this has to be considered else only certain types of decks are viable at the highest levels of play. [New Player] </b><br />
<br />
Whoa... this one is going to take some time. (= This isn&#39;t exactly a &quot;Meta&quot; question, but it does fall under the &quot;Bigger Picture&quot; category. I will try to address all of your points, but if I don&#39;t please feel free to contact me again.<br />
<br />
It sounds like this is an issue of time, and time management (both of the tournament and the games). Decipher has little to say about the location of tournaments, other than they must be in public places. They can not mandate that the location have a timer on hand for all to see. I know that at the larger tournaments that they run they do provide a timer for the players. However when it comes to smaller tournaments it&#39;s up to the director to have a timer available to them, not necessarily available to all of the players. I myself only use my wraist watch when I&#39;m running a local tournament. My advice to players would be to bring their own timer to keep an &quot;unoffical&quot; eye on time if they feel they need to always know hpw much time is left in the round.<br />
<br />
In terms of waiting 10 minutes in between rounds, again that is something that Decipher has little control over. Every local tournament is different and every director is different. I like to let the players get their starting bid and fellowships set up before I start the 45 minutes. Some directors consider this to be part of the game and as such it falls within the 45 minutes. I see both sides of the arguement. I do what I do because I don&#39;t like timed games. (= If you notice your director extenting the time control to his advantage you need to make it aware to him and the other players. If he doesn&#39;t change, maybe someone else should direct your tournaments. <br />
<br />
Lastly, timed games... like I said I don&#39;t like them. But it&#39;s not because I think there isn&#39;t enough time in the round to play a full game. I think 45 minutes is more than enough time as long as you have 2 knowledgable players. But never the less they happen and usually that means someone will leave the table unhappy. Again, it&#39;s all about time management. If you think your player is playing slow it&#39;s up to you to notify the director. If you think it&#39;s because you had to use some of your time to bid and get out your starting fellowship, then perhaps you can suggest to your local director to not start the timer until everyone is ready to start their game. That will more than likely depend on the director and the size of the tournament. No one likes having to wait to start their game, just because one game isn&#39;t ready to start yet. As for going second, I don&#39;t really know if there is a fix to this. one of the things I like most about Lord of the Rings is the openning bid. You have to weigh your options and determine how much you really want to be able to choose about going first or second. I think too many players take that for granted. If you are tired of always going second, and feel it&#39;s affecting your performance, then I suggest you start bidding higher. You&#39;ll have to change to deck a little to be prepared for the higher bid, but it is still entirely withing your control. As such, I don&#39;t think there is a need for rules that allow the second player an extra turn. If I don&#39;t like always going second, I&#39;ll do something about it.<br />
<br />
In closing, all I can say is that at Decipher&#39;s tournaments they try to do whatever they can to make the games fair and fun. I try to do the same in my tournaments, whether I&#39;m running them at big conventions or at my local retailer. We have little say in how they are run at your local store other than general guidelines. However, you as the player do have lots to say. If you think your local tournaments aren&#39;t being run at the standard Decipher has set, then there are some things you can do about it. Give it a try and if every you need help I&#39;m always willing to see what I can do. (=<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about SW Rulings:</h3><br />
<br />
No questions this time.<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
